Basics primer¶

String literals¶

https://docs.python.org/3/reference/lexical_analysis.html#string-and-bytes-literals

The character \ is used to escape characters that otherwise have a special meaning.

Escape Sequence Meaning
\\ Backslash (\)
\' Single quote (')
\" Double quote (")
\n ASCII Linefeed (LF)
\r ASCII Carriage Return (CR)
\t ASCII Horizontal Tab (TAB)

New lines on Windows: "\r\n"
New lines on Linux/Mac/Python: "\n"

Advanced for-loops¶

Assume you want to print both the position and the value of list elements.

In [1]:
l = ["Hello", "beautiful", "World"]
In [2]:
i = 0
for x in l:
    print(i, x)
    i += 1

0 Hello
1 beautiful
2 World
In [3]:
for i in range(len(l)):
    print(i, l[i])

0 Hello
1 beautiful
2 World
In [4]:
# enumerate: generator that yields tuples (index, element)
for i, x in enumerate(l):
    print(i, x)

0 Hello
1 beautiful
2 World

Assume you want to iterate over two or more lists at the same time.

In [5]:
l1 = [1, 2, 3, 4]
l2 = ["one", "two", "three", "four"]
l3 = ["eins", "zwei", "drei", "vier"]
In [6]:
# zip: yields a tuple of elements from the passed iterables, by position
for x1, x2, x3 in zip(l1, l2, l3):
    print(x1, x2, x3)

1 one eins
2 two zwei
3 three drei
4 four vier

Methods of file objects¶

Note: file object remember the current position in the file

Method Description
read() Reads the file and returns its content as a string
read(n) Same as read(), but reads at most n characters
readline() Reads a single line (terminated by "\n") of the file
readlines() Reads all lines of the file and returns them as a list
write(s) Writes the string s to the file

Exercise¶

Write a function that reads a CSV file into a dictionary.

Dictionary keys: column names (string)
Dictionary values: lists of column values (strings, for now)

In [9]:
def read_csv(file):
    d = {}
    with open(file, 'r') as f:
        header = f.readline().strip()
        columns = header.split(',')
        for column in columns:
            d[column] = []
        for line in f:  # iterate over remaining lines
            line_values = line.strip().split(',')
            for column, line_value in zip(columns, line_values):
                d[column].append(line_value)
    return d

Write a function that writes a dictionary into a CSV file.

Dictionary keys: column names (string)
Dictionary values: lists of column values (strings, for now)

In [11]:
def write_csv(file, d, line_ending='\n'):
    with open(file, 'w') as f:
        columns = list(d.keys())
        header = ','.join(columns) + line_ending
        f.write(header)
        for i in range(len(d[columns[0]])):
            line_values = []
            for column in columns:
                line_values.append(d[column][i])
            line = ','.join(line_values) + line_ending
            f.write(line)

Fetching data¶

In [21]:
# 2019-nCoV Data Repository by Johns Hopkins CSSE
confirmed_url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_confirmed_global.csv'
recovered_url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_recovered_global.csv'
deaths_url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_deaths_global.csv'

def fetch_covid(url, value_name):
    df = pd.read_csv(url).fillna('')  # groupby drops np.nan keys!
    groups = df.groupby(['Country/Region', 'Province/State', 'Lat', 'Long'])
    def melt_group_dates(group):
        group = group.drop(columns=groups.keys)
        group = group.melt(var_name='Date', value_name=value_name)
        group['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(group['Date'])
        return group.set_index('Date')
    return groups.apply(melt_group_dates).reset_index()

covid_cases = fetch_covid(confirmed_url, 'Confirmed')
covid_cases = pd.merge(covid_cases, fetch_covid(recovered_url, 'Recovered'))
covid_cases = pd.merge(covid_cases, fetch_covid(deaths_url, 'Deaths'))
covid_cases.to_csv('../Data/covid19.csv', index=False)

Indexing cheat sheet¶

Recommendation: primarily use .loc and .iloc (more explicit)
For indexing on Series (similar), primarily use s[x] (index by position/mask)

Method Description & index arguments
df.x Index by column label (only for valid column names)
df[x] Mixed indexing
Slices: index by row position
Strings/Lists: index by column label(s)
Boolean arrays: index by row mask
df.loc[x, y] Selection by label
(Lists of) labels: row/column label(s), e.g. 123 "Date"
Boolean arrays, e.g. np.ones(nrows, dtype=bool)
Slices, e.g. 0:5 unexpected behavior in some cases --> avoid!
df.iloc[x, y] Selection by position
(Lists of) integers: row/column position(s), e.g. 0, -1
Boolean arrays, e.g. np.ones(ncols, dtype=bool)
Slices, e.g. 0:5, : (use "empty" slices to select everything)
df.at[x, y]
df.iat[x, y]		 Similar to .loc and .iloc, but for selecting single values

Plotting examples¶

In [45]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

case_type = 'Confirmed'
countries = ['Austria', 'Germany', 'Switzerland', 'United Kingdom', 'US']

def plot_covid_cases(df, case_type, countries):
    df = df.loc[df['Country/Region'].isin(countries), :]
    for country, g in df.groupby('Country/Region'):
        cases_by_day = g.groupby('Date')[case_type].sum()
        plt.plot(cases_by_day.index, cases_by_day.values, label=country)
        
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
plot_covid_cases(covid_cases, case_type, countries)
plt.yscale('log')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel(case_type)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.legend()
plt.show()
In [46]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.basemap import Basemap

case_thres = 1000
case_type = 'Deaths'

def plot_covid_map(df, case_type, case_thres=1000):
    m = Basemap(projection='cyl')
    m.fillcontinents(color='peru')
    groupby_columns = ['Country/Region', 'Province/State', 'Lat', 'Long']
    for k, g in df.fillna('').groupby(groupby_columns):
        country_region, province_state, lat, long = k
        num_cases = g.loc[g['Date'] == g['Date'].max(), case_type].sum()
        if num_cases > case_thres:
            x, y = m(long, lat)
            p = m.plot(x, y, 'o', color='darkblue')
            plt.text(x, y, province_state or country_region)
        
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 12))
plot_covid_map(covid_cases, case_type, case_thres)
plt.title(f'Provinces/states with more than {case_thres} {case_type.lower()}')
plt.show()

from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture

gmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=2, tol=1e-9, verbose=2)
predictions = gmm.fit_predict(panCK_transformed[:, None])
probabilities = gmm.predict_proba(panCK_transformed[:, None])

In [53]:
panCK_positive_class = gmm.means_.argmax()
n_panCK_negative = np.sum(predictions != panCK_positive_class)
n_panCK_positive = np.sum(predictions == panCK_positive_class)
